ggi\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[44th British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Award]]\n|[[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|Martin Scorsese and Irwin Winkler\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Director]]\n|Martin Scorsese\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[BAFTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n|Martin Scorsese and Nicholas Pileggi\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor]]\n|[[Robert De Niro]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[BAFTA Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n|Thelma Schoonmaker\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n|[[Michael Ballhaus]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[BAFTA Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]\n|Richard Bruno\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Directors Guild of America Award]]\n|[[Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding Directing \u2013 Feature Film|Outstanding Directing \u2013 Feature]]\n|Martin Scorsese\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Writers Guild of America Award]]\n|[[Writers Guild of America Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n|Martin Scorsese and Nicholas Pileggi\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[C\u00e9sar Awards 1991|C\u00e9sar Award]]\n|[[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Foreign Film|Best Non-French Film]]\n|Martin Scorsese and Irwin Winkler\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[47th Venice International Film Festival|Venice Film Festival]]\n|[[Silver Lion]] for Best Director<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmaffinity.com/en/awards.php?award_id=venice&year=1990 |title=47th Venice Film Festival |year=1990 |accessdate=November 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014043044/http://www.filmaffinity.com/en/awards.php?award_id=venice&year=1990|archive-date=October 14, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|Martin Scorsese\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Audience Award\n|Martin Scorsese\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Filmcritica \"Bastone Bianco\" Award\n|Martin Scorsese\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[1990 New York Film Critics Circle Awards|New York Film Critics Circle Award]]\n|[[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|Martin Scorsese and Irwin Winkler\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n|Martin Scorsese\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n|Robert De Niro\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards 1990|Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award]]\n|[[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|Martin Scorsese and Irwin Winkler\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n|Martin Scorsese\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n|Joe Pesci\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n|Lorraine Bracco\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n|Michael Ballhaus\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[National Board of Review Awards 1990|National Board of Review Award]]\n|[[National Board of Review Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n|Joe Pesci\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Boston Society of Film Critics Awards 1990|Boston Society of Film Critics Award]]\n|[[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|Martin Scorsese and Irwin Winkler\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n|Martin Scorsese\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n|Joe Pesci\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Chicago Film Critics Association Awards 1990|Chicago Film Critics Association Award]]\n|[[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|Martin Scorsese and Irwin Winkler\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n|Martin Scorsese\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n|Joe Pesci\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n|Lorraine Bracco\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n|Martin Scorsese and Nicholas Pileggi\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[National Society of Film Critics Awards 1990|National Society of Film Critics Award]]\n|[[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|Martin Scorsese and Irwin Winkler\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n|Martin Scorsese\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[44th Bodil Awards|Bodil Award]]\n|[[Bodil Award for Best American Film|Best American Film]]\n|Martin Scorsese and Irwin Winkler\n|{{won}}\n|}\n\n== Legacy ==\n''Goodfellas'' is #94 on the [[American Film Institute]]'s \"[[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Movies|100 Years, 100 Movies]]\" list and moved up to #92 on its [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movies (10th Anniversary Edition)]] from 2007. In June 2008, the AFI put ''Goodfellas'' at #2 on their [[AFI's 10 Top 10]]\u2014the best ten films in ten \"classic\" American film genres\u2014after polling over 1,500 people from the movie-related community.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/Movies_ballot_06.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years Movies: Ballot |website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014130225/http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/Movies_ballot_06.pdf|archive-date=October 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Goodfellas'' was regarded as the second-best in the gangster film genre (after ''[[The Godfather]]'').<ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |title=AFI's 10 Top 10 |date=June 17, 2008 |url=http://www.afi.com/10top10/gangster.html |accessdate=June 18, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116145351/http://www.afi.com/10top10/gangster.html|archive-date=January 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2000, the United States [[Library of Congress]] deemed the film \"culturally significant\" and selected it for preservation in the [[National Film Registry]].\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] named ''Goodfellas'' the \"best mob movie ever\" and placed it among the ten best films of the 1990s.<ref name=\"Scorsese\">{{cite episode |title=Best Films of the '90s |series=[[At the Movies with Ebert & Roeper]] |airdate=2000-02-27 |url=http://tvplex.go.com/buenavista/ebertandroeper/specials/bestof90s.html |accessdate=March 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808062528/http://tvplex.go.com/buenavista/ebertandroeper/specials/bestof90s.html |archivedate=August 8, 2007 }}</ref> In December 2002, a UK film critics poll in ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' ranked the film #4 on their list of the 10 Best Films of the Last 25 Years.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[Sight and Sound]] |title=Modern Times |date=December 2002 |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/feature/63/ |accessdate=August 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312084249/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/feature/63/ |archivedate=March 12, 2012 }}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' included ''Goodfellas'' in their list of [[Time's All-Time 100 Movies]].<ref name=\"Schickel\">{{cite news |last=Schickel |first=Richard |title=All-Time 100 Movies |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=http://www.time.com/time/2005/100movies/0,23220,goodfellas,00.html |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |date=February 12, 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122115212/http://www.time.com/time/2005/100movies/0,23220,goodfellas,00.html|archive-date=January 22, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Channel 4]]'' placed ''Goodfellas'' at #10 in their 2002 poll ''The 100 Greatest Films'', ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' listed ''Goodfellas'' at #6 on their \"500 Greatest Movies Of All Time,\"<ref>{{cite news |title=The 500 Greatest Movies Of All Time |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |url=http://www.empireonline.com/500/94.asp |accessdate=December 2, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101010231/http://www.empireonline.com/500/94.asp|archive-date=November 1, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and ''[[Total Film]]'' voted ''Goodfellas'' #1 as the [[List of films considered the best|greatest film of all time]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4370918.stm |publisher=BBC NEWS |title=Goodfellas named \"greatest movie\" |date=October 25, 2005|access-date=June 29, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617052719/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4370918.stm|archive-date=June 17, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]]'' listed Joe Pesci's Tommy DeVito as #96 on its list of \"The 100 Greatest Movie Characters of All Time,\" calling him \"perhaps the single most irredeemable character ever put on film.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=The 100 Greatest Movie Characters of All Time |work=[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]] |url=http://www.premiere.com/features/1539/the-100-greatest-movie-characters-of-all-time-page2.html |accessdate=March 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080317001135/http://www.premiere.com/features/1539/the-100-greatest-movie-characters-of-all-time-page2.html |archivedate=March 17, 2008 }}</ref> ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' ranked Tommy DeVito #59 in their \"The 100 Greatest Movie Characters\" poll.<ref>{{cite news |title=The 100 Greatest Movie Characters |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |url=http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=59 |accessdate=December 2, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107044642/http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=59|archive-date=November 7, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Goodfellas'' inspired director [[David Chase]] to make the [[HBO]] television series ''[[The Sopranos]]''.\" He told [[Peter Bogdanovich]], \"''Goodfellas'' is a very important movie to me and ''Goodfellas'' really plowed that ... I found that movie very funny and brutal and it felt very real. And yet that was the first mob movie that Scorsese ever dealt with a mob crew. ... as opposed to say ''The Godfather'' ... which there's something operatic about it, classical, even the clothing and the cars. You know I mean I always think about ''Goodfellas'' when they go to their mother's house that night when they're eating, you know when she brings out her painting, that stuff is great. I mean ''The Sopranos'' learned a lot from that.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hbo.com/html/error/browser_message_b.html?return=http://www.hbo.com/the-sopranos/cast-and-crew/dr-elliot-kupferberg/interview/peter-bogdanovich.html |publisher=HBO |title=HBO: The Sopranos: Interview with Peter Bogdanovich |year=1999|access-date=September 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012090557/http://www.hbo.com/html/error/browser_message_b.html?return=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.hbo.com%2Fthe-sopranos%2Fcast-and-crew%2Fdr-elliot-kupferberg%2Finterview%2Fpeter-bogdanovich.html|archive-date=October 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Indeed, the film shares a total of 27 actors with ''The Sopranos'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/50-useless-but-genius-facts-about-goodfellas |title=50 genius facts about GoodFellas |work=ShortList |accessdate=December 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205114330/http://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/50-useless-but-genius-facts-about-goodfellas |archive-date=December 5, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> including Bracco, Sirico, Imperioli, [[Frank Pellegrino (actor)|Frank Pellegrino]], [[Tony Lip]], and Vincent, who all had major roles in Chase's HBO series.\n\nJuly 24, 2010, marked the 20th anniversary of the film's release. This milestone was celebrated with Henry Hill hosting a private screening for a select group of invitees at the [[Museum of the American Gangster]], in New York City.<ref>{{cite web |title=Goodfellas' Henry Hill Back in NYC for 20th Anniversary |work=WPIX-TV 11 |url=http://www.wpix.com/videobeta/20627713-2235-476f-b903-9675e153acfb/News/Goodfellas-Henry-Hill-Back-in-NYC-for-20th-Anniversary |date=July 24, 2010 |accessdate=October 9, 2010|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724024659/http://www.wpix.com/videobeta/20627713-2235-476f-b903-9675e153acfb/News/Goodfellas-Henry-Hill-Back-in-NYC-for-20th-Anniversary |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, it was announced that the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC Network]] had put a [[Television program|television series]] version of the movie in development. Pileggi was on board to co-write the adaptation with television writer-producer [[Jorge Zamacona]]. The two were set to executive produce with the film's producer [[Irwin Winkler]] and his son, David.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/01/goodfellas-series-in-the-works-at-amc-with-films-nicholas-pileggi-irwin-winkler/ |title='Goodfellas' Series In The Works At AMC With Film's Nicholas Pileggi & Irwin Winkler |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 10, 2012 |author=Andreeva, Nellie |accessdate=January 16, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113005924/http://www.deadline.com/2012/01/goodfellas-series-in-the-works-at-amc-with-films-nicholas-pileggi-irwin-winkler/|archive-date=January 13, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Luc Besson]]'s 2013 [[Crime film|crime]] [[comedy film]] [[The Family (2013 film)|''The Family'']] features a sequence where Giovanni Manzoni (''Goodfellas'' star De Niro), a gangster who is under [[witness protection]] for testifying against a member of his family, watches ''Goodfellas.''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.craveonline.com/entertainment/film/interviews/568945-exclusive-interview-luc-besson-on-the-family |title=Exclusive Interview: Luc Besson on The Family |last=Bibbiani |first=William |work=[[CraveOnline]] |date=September 11, 2013 |accessdate=May 7, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150506015417/http://www.craveonline.com/entertainment/film/interviews/568945-exclusive-interview-luc-besson-on-the-family|archive-date=May 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the [[ESPN]]-produced ''[[30 for 30]]'' series debuted ''Playing for the Mob'',<ref>{{cite book |url=http://espn.go.com/30for30/film?page=playingforthemob |publisher=ESPN |title=30 for 30: Playing for the Mob|access-date=March 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328185117/http://espn.go.com/30for30/film?page=playingforthemob|archive-date=March 28, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> the story about how Hill and his Pittsburgh associates, and several [[Boston College Eagles men's basketball|Boston College basketball]] players, committed the [[1978\u201379 Boston College basketball point shaving scandal|point shaving scandal]] during the 1978\u201379 season, an episode briefly mentioned in the movie. The documentary, narrated by Liotta, was set up so that the viewer needed to watch the film beforehand, to understand many of the references in the story.\n\nIn 2015, ''Goodfellas'' closed the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] with a screening of its 25th-anniversary remaster.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Gordon |title='GoodFellas' Anniversary Screening, Event to Close 2015 Tribeca Film Festival |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/goodfellas-tribeca-film-festival-2015-closing-night-1201455382/ |website=Variety.com |publisher=Variety |accessdate=March 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074023/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/goodfellas-tribeca-film-festival-2015-closing-night-1201455382/|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''[[American Film Institute]] Lists'''\n* [[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Movies]] - #94\n* [[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Movies (10th Anniversary Edition)]] - #92\n* [[AFI's 10 Top 10]] - #2 Gangster film\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite book |author=Kelly, Mary Pat |title=Martin Scorsese: A Journey |date=2003 |publisher=Thunder Mouth Press |isbn=978-1-56025-470-6}}\n* {{cite book |author1=Pileggi, Nicholas |author2=Scorsese, Martin |title=Goodfellas |date=1990 |publisher=Faber and Faber |isbn=978-0-571-16265-9}}\n* {{cite book |author=Pileggi, Nicholas |title=Wiseguy |date=1990 |publisher=Rei Mti |isbn=978-0-671-72322-4}}\n* {{cite book |author1=Thompson, David |author2=Christie, Ian |title=Scorsese on Scorsese |date=2004 |publisher=[[Faber and Faber]] |isbn=978-0-571-22002-1}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.gq.com/entertainment/movies-and-tv/201010/goodfellas-making-of-behind-the-scenes-interview-scorsese-deniro |title=Getting Made The Scorsese Way |work=GQ |date=October 2010}}\n* {{IMDb title|0099685|Goodfellas}}\n* {{AllRovi title|20351|Goodfellas}}\n* {{tcmdb title|76747|Goodfellas}}\n* {{Mojo title|goodfellas|Goodfellas}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|1032176-goodfellas}}\n* {{Metacritic film|goodfellas|Goodfellas}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.chasingthefrog.com/reelfaces/goodfellas.php |title=Reel Faces: Fact vs. Fiction |website=Chasingthefrog.com}}\n\n{{Martin Scorsese}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for ''Goodfellas''\n| list1 =\n{{BAFTA Best Film 1981\u20132000}}\n{{Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Film}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Film}}\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n}}\n\n{{Portal bar|1990s|Film|United States}}\n\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:1990s crime films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American crime films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Best Film BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films about drugs]]\n[[Category:Mafia films]]\n[[Category:Films about organized crime in the United States]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Martin Scorsese]]\n[[Category:Films based on biographies]]\n[[Category:Crime films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Films based on non-fiction books about organized crime]]\n[[Category:Lucchese crime family]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Supporting Actor Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films whose director won the Best Direction BAFTA Award]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Adapted Screenplay BAFTA Award]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Martin Scorsese]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Irwin Winkler]]\n[[Category:Films set in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1950s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1960s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1980]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|1990 crime film directed by Martin Scorsese}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Goodfellas\n| image          = Goodfellas.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Martin Scorsese]]\n| producer       = [[Irwin Winkler]]\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Nicholas Pileggi]]\n* Martin Scorsese\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Wiseguy (book)|Wiseguy]]''|Nicholas Pileggi}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Robert De Niro]]\n* [[Ray Liotta]]\n* [[Joe Pesci]]\n* [[Lorraine Bracco]]\n* [[Paul Sorvino]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Michael Ballhaus]]\n| editing        = [[Thelma Schoonmaker]]\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros.]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1990|9|9|[[47th Venice International Film Festival|Venice]]|1990|9|19|United States}}\n| runtime        = 145 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 145:17--><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/goodfellas-film |title=''Goodfellas'' (18) |work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=September 17, 1990 |accessdate=October 22, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303113514/http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/goodfellas-film | archive-date=March 3, 2016 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $25 million<ref name=Thompson />\n| gross          = $46.8 million<ref name=\"Box Office Mojo\" />\n}}\n'''''Goodfellas''''' (stylized '''''GoodFellas''''') is a 1990 American [[crime film]] directed by [[Martin Scorsese]], produced by [[Irwin Winkler]] and distributed by [[Warner Bros.]] It is an [[film adaptation|adaptation]] of the 1985 non-fiction book ''[[Wiseguy (book)|Wiseguy]]'' by [[Nicholas Pileggi]], who co-wrote the screenplay with Scorsese. The film narrates the rise and fall of mob associate [[Henry Hill]] and his friends and family from 1955 to 1980.\n\nScorsese initially titled the film ''Wise Guy'' and postponed making it; later, he and Pileggi changed the title to ''Goodfellas''. To prepare for their roles in the film, [[Robert De Niro]], [[Joe Pesci]] and [[Ray Liotta]] often spoke with Pileggi, who shared research material left over from writing the book. According to Pesci, improvisation and ad-libbing came out of rehearsals wherein Scorsese gave the actors freedom to do whatever they wanted. The director made transcripts of these sessions, took the lines he liked most and put them into a revised script, which the cast worked from during principal photography.\n\n''Goodfellas'' premiered at the [[47th Venice International Film Festival]] on September 9, 1990, where Scorsese was awarded with [[Silver Lion]] for Best Director, and was released in the United States on September 19, 1990. The film was made on a budget of $25 million, and grossed $46.8 million. The critical consensus on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] calls it \"arguably the high point of Martin Scorsese's career\". The film was nominated for six [[Academy Awards]], including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]], with Pesci winning for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]. The film won five awards from the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]], including [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]] and [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Director]]. Additionally, ''Goodfellas'' was named the year's best film by various critics' groups.\n\n''Goodfellas'' is widely regarded as one of the greatest films in the gangster genre. In 2000, it was deemed \"culturally, historically, and aesthetically significant\" and selected for preservation in the [[National Film Registry]] by the United States [[Library of Congress]]. Its content and style have been emulated in numerous other films and television series.<ref>{{cite news |last=Merrie |first=Stephanie |title='Goodfellas' is 25. Here's an incomplete list of all the movies that have ripped it off |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/style-blog/wp/2015/04/29/goodfellas-is-25-heres-an-incomplete-list-of-all-the-movies-that-have-ripped-it-off/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 29, 2015 |accessdate=March 12, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728121953/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/style-blog/wp/2015/04/29/goodfellas-is-25-heres-an-incomplete-list-of-all-the-movies-that-have-ripped-it-off/ | archive-date=July 28, 2015 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature films should be set between 400-700 words. -->\nIn 1955, a young [[Henry Hill]] becomes enamored of the criminal life and [[Italian-American Mafia|Mafia]] presence in his working class Italian-American neighborhood in [[Brooklyn]]. He begins working for local ''[[caporegime]]'' Paul \"Paulie\" Cicero and his associates: James \"Jimmy the Gent\" Conway, an Irish truck hijacker and gangster, and Tommy DeVito, a fellow juvenile delinquent. Henry begins as a [[fence (criminal)|fence]] for Jimmy, gradually working his way up to more serious crimes. The three associates spend most of their nights in the 1960s at the [[Copacabana (nightclub)|Copacabana nightclub]] carousing with women. Henry starts dating [[Karen Friedman Hill|Karen Friedman]], a Jewish woman. She is initially troubled by Henry's criminal activities but is eventually seduced by his glamorous lifestyle. She marries him, despite her parents' disapproval.\n\nIn 1970, [[William Bentvena|Billy Batts]], a [[made man]] in the [[Gambino crime family|Gambino crew]] who was recently released from prison, repeatedly insults Tommy at a nightclub owned by Henry. This provoked his murder by Tommy and Jimmy. The unsanctioned murder of a made man invites retribution; realizing this, Jimmy, Henry, and Tommy cover up the murder by burying the body in Upstate New York. Six months later, however, Jimmy learns that the burial site is slated for development, prompting them to exhume and relocate the decomposing corpse.\n\nIn 1974, Karen harasses Henry's mistress Janice and holds Henry at gunpoint. Henry moves in with Janice, but Paulie insists that he should return to Karen after collecting a debt from a gambler in [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]] with Jimmy. Upon returning, Jimmy and Henry are arrested after being turned in by the gambler's sister, an FBI typist, and they receive ten-year prison sentences. In order to support his family on the outside, Henry has drugs smuggled in by Karen and sells them to a fellow inmate from [[Pittsburgh]]. In 1978, Henry is paroled and expands this cocaine business against Paulie's orders, soon involving Jimmy and Tommy.\n\nJimmy organizes a crew to raid the [[Lufthansa heist|Lufthansa vault]] at the [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|JFK Airport]], stealing several millions in cash and jewelry. After some members purchase expensive items against Jimmy's orders and the getaway truck is found by police, he has most of the crew murdered. In his [[Voice-over|voiceover]] narration, as dead bodies are being discovered all over the city, Henry theorizes that Jimmy would have killed them anyway rather than share the profits of the heist. Tommy and Henry are spared by Jimmy. Tommy, however, is later led to believe that he is to become a made man, but is ultimately shot dead on the way to the ceremony in retribution for Batts' murder.\n\nBy 1980, Henry has become a nervous wreck from cocaine use and insomnia. He sets up a drug deal with his Pittsburgh associates, but is arrested by narcotics agents, and jailed. After bailing him out, Karen explains that she flushed $60,000 worth of cocaine down the toilet to prevent FBI agents from finding it during their raid, leaving them virtually penniless. Feeling betrayed by Henry's drug dealing, Paulie gives him $3,200 and ends their association. Henry meets Jimmy at a diner and is asked to travel on a hit assignment, but the novelty of such a request makes him suspicious. Henry realizes that Jimmy plans to have him and Karen killed, prompting his decision to become an [[informant]] and enroll, with his family, in the [[United States Federal Witness Protection Program|witness protection program]]. He gives sufficient testimony to have Paulie and Jimmy arrested and convicted. Henry is grateful to be alive, but he is forced out of his gangster life and has to readjust to normal life once again; he narrates, \"I'm an average nobody. I get to live the rest of my life like a [[schnook]].\"\n\nThe end title cards state that Henry is still a protected witness as of 1990, but that he was arrested in 1987 in [[Seattle]] for narcotics conspiracy, receiving five years' probation. He has been clean since then. He and Karen separated in 1989 after 25 years of marriage, while Paulie died the previous year in [[Federal Medical Center, Fort Worth|Fort Worth Federal Prison]] at age 73 from respiratory illness. Jimmy is serving a 20 years to life sentence in a New York prison for murder, in which he will be paroled in 2004, when he will be 78 years old.\n\n== Cast ==\n<!-- Please do not add real life people who are fictionalized in this film to this list. It violates several sections of the 'Manual of Style' and such additions will be removed. THE CAST LIST IS ACCORDING TO THE END CREDITS OF THE FILM per WP:FILMCAST-->\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Robert De Niro]] as James Conway\n* [[Ray Liotta]] as [[Henry Hill]]\n* [[Joe Pesci]] as Tommy DeVito\n* [[Lorraine Bracco]] as [[Karen Friedman Hill|Karen Hill]]\n* [[Paul Sorvino]] as Paul Cicero\n* [[Frank Sivero]] as Frankie Carbone\n* [[Tony Darrow]] as Sonny Bunz\n* [[Frank Vincent]] as [[William Bentvena|Billy Batts]]\n* [[Chuck Low]] as Morris Kessler\n* [[Frank DiLeo]] as Tuddy Cicero\n* [[Henny Youngman]] as Himself\n* Gina Mastrogiacomo as Janice Rossi\n* [[Catherine Scorsese]] as Tommy's mother\n* [[Charles Scorsese]] as Vinnie\n* [[Suzanne Shepard]] as Karen's mother\n* [[Debi Mazar]] as Sandy\n* [[Margo Winkler]] as Belle Kessler\n* Welker White as Lois Byrd\n* [[Jerry Vale]] as Himself\n* Julie Garfield as Mickey Conway\n* Christopher Serrone as Young Henry\n* Elaine Kagan as Henry's mother\n* [[Beau Starr]] as Henry's father\n* [[Kevin Corrigan]] as Michael Hill\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as Spider\n* Robbie Vinton as [[Bobby Vinton]]\n* John Williams as Johnny Roastbeef\n* [[Samuel L. Jackson]] as Stacks Edwards\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\n''Goodfellas'' is based on New York crime reporter [[Nicholas Pileggi]]'s book ''Wiseguy''.<ref>{{cite news |work=AV Club |title=Goodfellas turned Wiseguy's simple prose into cinematic gold |author=Vlastelica, Ryan |date=September 18, 2015 |url=http://www.avclub.com/article/goodfellas-turned-wiseguys-simple-prose-cinematic--224013|access-date=September 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150918190329/http://www.avclub.com/article/goodfellas-turned-wiseguys-simple-prose-cinematic--224013|archive-date=September 18, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Martin Scorsese did not intend to make another mob film, but he saw a review of Pileggi's book, which he then read while working on the set of ''[[The Color of Money]]'' in 1986.<ref name=\"Murphy, Kathleen\">{{cite news |last=Malcolm |first=Derek |title=Made Men |work=[[Film Comment]] |date=September\u2013October 1990}}</ref><ref name=\"Goodwin, Richard\">{{cite news |last=Goodwin |first=Richard |title=The Making of ''Goodfellas'' |work=[[Hotdog Magazine|Hotdog]]}}</ref> He had always been fascinated by the [[American Mafia|mob]] lifestyle and was drawn to Pileggi's book because he thought it was the most honest portrayal of gangsters he had ever read.<ref name= Linfield>{{cite news |last=Linfield |first=Susan |title=''Goodfellas'' Looks at the Banality of Mob Life |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 16, 1990 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/09/16/movies/film-goodfellas-looks-at-the-banality-of-mob-life.html|access-date=December 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007070355/http://www.nytimes.com/1990/09/16/movies/film-goodfellas-looks-at-the-banality-of-mob-life.html|archive-date=October 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> After reading the book, Scorsese knew what approach he wanted to take, \"To begin ''Goodfellas'' like a gunshot and have it get faster from there, almost like a two-and-a-half-hour trailer. I think it's the only way you can really sense the exhilaration of the lifestyle, and to get a sense of why a lot of people are attracted to it.\"<ref name=Clark>{{cite news |last=Clark |first=Mike |title=''GoodFellas'' step from his childhood |work=[[USA Today]] |date=September 19, 1990}}</ref> According to Pileggi, Scorsese cold-called the writer and told him, \"I've been waiting for this book my entire life,\" to which Pileggi replied, \"I've been waiting for this phone call my entire life.\"<ref name=\"Kelly, Mary Pat\">{{cite news |last=Kelly |first=Mary Pat |title=Martin Scorsese: A Journey |publisher=Thunder Mouth Press |date=March 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/goodfellas-classic-feature |title=The Making of Goodfellas |date=November 1990 |work=Empire Magazine |accessdate=June 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924053255/http://www.empireonline.com/features/goodfellas-classic-feature|archive-date=September 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nScorsese decided to postpone making the film when funds materialized in 1988 to make ''[[The Last Temptation of Christ (film)|The Last Temptation of Christ]]''. He was drawn to the documentary aspects of Pileggi's book. \"The book [''Wiseguy''] gives you a sense of the day-to-day life, the tedium, how they work, how they take over certain nightclubs, and for what reasons. It shows how it's done.\"<ref name=\"Kelly, Mary Pat\" /> He saw ''Goodfellas'' as the third film in an unplanned trilogy of films that examined the lives of Italian Americans \"from slightly different angles.\"<ref name=Gilbert>{{cite news |last=Gilbert |first=Matthew |title=Scorsese Tackles the Mob |work=[[Boston Globe]] |date=September 16, 1990}}</ref> He has often described the film as \"a mob home movie\" that is about money, because \"that's what they're really in business for.\"<ref name=Linfield /> Two weeks in advance of the filming, the real [[Henry Hill]] was paid $480,000.<ref name=\"Hughes pp176-177\" />\n\n=== Screenplay ===\nScorsese and Pileggi collaborated on the screenplay, and over the course of the 12 drafts it took to reach the ideal script, the reporter realized \"the visual styling had to be completely redone... So we decided to share credit.\"<ref name=\"Kelly, Mary Pat\" /><ref name=\"Hughes pp176-177\" /> They chose the sections of the book they liked and put them together like building blocks.<ref name=Thompson>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=David |authorlink=David M. Thompson |author2=Ian Christie |authorlink2=Ian Christie (film scholar) |title=Scorsese on Scorsese |pages=150\u2013161 |publisher=[[Faber and Faber]] |year=1996}}</ref> Scorsese persuaded Pileggi that they did not need to follow a traditional narrative structure. The director wanted to take the gangster film and deal with it episode by episode, but start in the middle and move backwards and forwards. Scorsese compacted scenes, realizing that, if they were kept short, \"the impact after about an hour and a half would be terrific.\"<ref name=Thompson /> He wanted to do the voiceover like the opening of ''[[Jules and Jim]]'' (1962) and use \"all the basic tricks of the [[French New Wave|New Wave]] from around 1961.\"<ref name=Thompson /> The names of several real-life gangsters were altered for the film: [[Thomas DeSimone|Tommy \"Two Gun\" DeSimone]] became the character Tommy DeVito; [[Paul Vario]] became Paulie Cicero, and [[James Burke (gangster)|Jimmy \"The Gent\" Burke]] was portrayed as Jimmy Conway.<ref name=\"Hughes pp176-177\">{{cite book |author=Hughes, Howard |title=Crime Wave: The Filmgoers' Guide to the Great Crime Movies |pages=176\u2013177}}</ref> Scorsese initially titled the film ''Wise Guy'', but later, he and Pileggi decided to change the title of their film to ''Goodfellas'' because two contemporary projects, the 1986 [[Brian De Palma]] film ''[[Wise Guys (1986 film)|Wise Guys]]'' and the 1987\u20131990 TV series ''[[Wiseguy]]'' had used similar titles.<ref name=Thompson />\n\n=== Casting ===\nOnce [[Robert De Niro]] agreed to play Conway, Scorsese was able to secure the money needed to make the film.<ref name=\"Goodwin, Richard\" /> The director cast [[Ray Liotta]] after De Niro saw him in [[Jonathan Demme]]'s ''[[Something Wild (1986 film)|Something Wild]]'' (1986), and Scorsese was surprised by \"his explosive energy\" in that film.<ref name=Gilbert /> Liotta had read Pileggi's book when it came out and was fascinated by it. A couple of years afterwards, his agent told him Scorsese was going to direct a film version. In 1988, he met the director over a period of a couple of months and auditioned for the film.<ref name=Linfield /> He campaigned aggressively for a role, but the studio wanted a well-known actor. He later said \"I think they would've rather had [[Eddie Murphy]] than me.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Portman |first=Jamie |title=''Goodfellas'' Star Prefers Quiet Life |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=October 1, 1990}}</ref>\n\nTo prepare for the role, De Niro consulted with Pileggi, who had research material that had been discarded while writing the book.<ref name=Arnold>{{cite news |last=Arnold |first=Gary |title=Real Fellas Talk about Mob Film |work=[[The Washington Times]] |date=September 25, 1990}}</ref> De Niro often called Hill several times a day to ask how Burke walked, held his cigarette, and so on.<ref name=\"Wolf, Buck\">{{cite news |last=Wolf |first=Buck |title=Rap Star 50 Cent Joins Movie Mobsters |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=November 8, 2005 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/WolfFiles/story?id=1338853 |accessdate=June 24, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070312054917/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/WolfFiles/story?id=1338853|archive-date=March 12, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Papamichael, Stella\">{{cite news |last=Papamichael |first=Stella |title=GoodFellas: Special Edition DVD (1990) |publisher=BBC |date=October 22, 2004 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/10/22/goodfellas_se_2004_dvd_review.shtml |accessdate=June 24, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070717052614/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/10/22/goodfellas_se_2004_dvd_review.shtml |archive-date=July 17, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> Driving to and from the set, Liotta listened to FBI audio cassette tapes of Hill, so he could practice speaking like his real-life counterpart.<ref name=\"Papamichael, Stella\" /> To research her role, [[Lorraine Bracco]] tried to get close to a mob wife but was unable to, because they exist in a very tight-knit community. She decided not to meet the real Karen, saying she \"thought it would be better if the creation came from me. I used her life with her parents as an emotional guideline for the role.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Witchel |first=Alex |title=A Mafia Wife Makes Lorraine Bracco a Princess |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 27, 1990}}</ref> [[Paul Sorvino]] had no problem finding the voice and walk of his character, but found it challenging finding what he called \"that kernel of coldness and absolute hardness that is antithetical to my nature except when my family is threatened.\"<ref name=\"Van Gelder\">{{cite news |last=Van Gelder |first=Lawrence |title=At the Movies |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 12, 1990}}</ref>\n\n=== Photography ===\nThe film was shot on location in [[Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York state]], [[New Jersey]], and parts of [[Long Island]] during the spring and summer of 1989, with a budget of $25 million.<ref name=\"Hughes pp176-177\" /> Scorsese broke the film down into sequences and [[storyboard]]ed everything because of the complicated style throughout. The filmmaker stated, \"[I] wanted lots of movement and I wanted it to be throughout the whole picture, and I wanted the style to kind of break down by the end, so that by [Henry's] last day as a wiseguy, it's as if the whole picture would be out of control, give the impression he's just going to spin off the edge and fly out.\"<ref name=\"Murphy, Kathleen\" /> He added that the film's style comes from the first two or three minutes of ''[[Jules and Jim]]'' (1962): extensive narration, quick edits, [[Freeze-frame shot|freeze frames]], and multiple locale switches.<ref name=Clark /> It was this reckless attitude towards convention that mirrored the attitude of many of the gangsters in the film. Scorsese remarked, \"So if you do the movie, you say, 'I don't care if there's too much narration. Too many quick cuts?\u2014That's too bad.' It's that kind of really punk attitude we're trying to show.\"<ref name=Clark /> He adopted a frenetic style to almost overwhelm the audience with images and information.<ref name=Thompson /> He also put plenty of detail in every frame because he believed the gangster life is so rich. Freeze frames were used as Scorsese wanted images that stopped \"because a point was being reached\" in Henry's life.<ref name=Thompson />\n\n[[Joe Pesci]] did not judge his character but found the scene where he kills Spider for talking back to his character hard to do, because he had trouble justifying the action until he forced himself to feel the way Tommy did.<ref name=Linfield /> Lorraine Bracco found the shoot to be an emotionally difficult one because it was such a male-dominated cast, and she realized if she did not make her \"work important, it would probably end up on the cutting room floor.\"<ref name=Linfield /> When it came to the relationship between Henry and Karen, Bracco saw no difference between an abused wife and her character.<ref name=Linfield />\n\nAccording to Pesci, improvisation and ad-libbing came out of rehearsals wherein Scorsese let the actors do whatever they wanted. He made transcripts of these sessions, took the lines the actors came up with that he liked best, and put them into a revised script that the cast worked from during principal photography.<ref name=Arnold /> For example, the scene where Tommy tells a story and Henry is responding to him\u2014the \"Funny how? Do I amuse you?\" scene\u2014is based on an actual event that Pesci experienced. Pesci was working as a waiter when he thought he was making a compliment to a mobster by saying he was \"funny\", however, the comment was not taken well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/goodfellas-joe-pesci-funny-how-scene-2015-5?r=US&IR=T|title=One of the most famous scenes in 'Goodfellas' is based on something that actually happened to Joe Pesci|publisher=businessinsider.com|date=May 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Ultimate Book of Gangster Movies: Featuring the 100 Greatest Gangster Films of All Time|author1=George Anastasia|author2=Glen Macnow|publisher=Running Press|year=2011|ISBN= 9780762441549|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=kY5tHAksa7kC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Ultimate+Book+of+Gangster+Movies:+Featuring+the+100+Greatest+Gangster+Films+of+All+Time&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivn5yd04HnAhUBUt8KHbkeAGkQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=funny&f=false}}</ref> It was worked on in rehearsals where he and Liotta improvised, and Scorsese recorded four to five takes, rewrote their dialogue, and inserted it into the script.<ref name=Kaplan>{{cite video |people=Kaplan, Jonah (writer and editor); Stephen Altobellow and Jeffrey Schwartz (producers) |date=2004 |format=Blu-ray Disc |title=Getting Made: The Making of ''Goodfellas'' |work=Goodfellas |publisher=[[Warner Home Video]] |isbn=1-4198-4306-0}}</ref> The dinner scene with Tommy's mother was largely improvised. Her painting of the bearded man with the dogs was based on a photograph from ''[[National Geographic]]'' magazine.<ref name=Godfrey>{{cite web |last1=Godfrey |first1=Alex |title=Whaddya want from me? |url=http://mrgodfrey.tumblr.com/post/66620475687/whaddya-want-from-me |website=mrgodfrey |date=November 2013|access-date=August 22, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904015411/http://mrgodfrey.tumblr.com/post/66620475687/whaddya-want-from-me|archive-date=September 4, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The cast did not meet [[Henry Hill]] until a few weeks before the film's premiere. Liotta met him in an undisclosed city; Hill had seen the film and told the actor that he loved it.<ref name=Linfield />\n\nThe long tracking shot through the Copacabana nightclub came about because of a practical problem: the filmmakers could not get permission to go in the short way, and this forced them to go round the back.<ref name=Thompson /> Scorsese decided to film the sequence in one unbroken shot in order to symbolize that Henry's entire life was ahead of him, commenting, \"It's his seduction of her [Karen] and it's also the lifestyle seducing him.\"<ref name=Thompson /> This sequence was shot eight times.<ref name=Kaplan />\n\nHenry's last day as a wiseguy was the hardest part of the film for Scorsese to shoot, because he wanted to properly show Henry's state of anxiety, paranoia, and racing thoughts caused by [[cocaine]] and [[Substituted amphetamine|amphetamines]] intoxication.<ref name=Thompson /> In an interview with movie critic [[Mark Cousins (film critic)|Mark Cousins]], Scorsese explained the reason for Pesci shooting at the camera at the end of the film, \"well that's a reference right to the end of ''[[The Great Train Robbery (1903 film)|The Great Train Robbery]]'', that's the way that ends, that film, and basically the plot of this picture is very similar to ''The Great Train Robbery''. It hasn't changed, 90 years later, it's the same story, the gun shots will always be there, he's always going to look behind his back, he's gotta have eyes behind his back, because they're gonna get him someday.\" The director ended the film with Henry regretting that he is no longer a wiseguy, about which Scorsese said, \"I think the audience should get angry at him and I would hope they do\u2014and maybe with the system which allows this.\"<ref name=Thompson />\n\n=== Post-production ===\nScorsese wanted to depict the film's violence realistically, \"cold, unfeeling and horrible. Almost incidental.\"<ref name=\"Goodwin, Richard\" /> However, he had to remove 10 frames of blood to ensure an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|R rating]] from the [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]].<ref name=Gilbert /> With a budget of $25 million, ''Goodfellas'' was Scorsese's most expensive film to that point but still only a medium-sized budget by Hollywood standards. It was also the first time he was obliged by Warner Bros. to preview the film. It was shown twice in California, and a lot of audiences were \"agitated\" by Henry's last day as a wise guy sequence. Scorsese argued that that was the point of the scene.<ref name=Thompson /> Scorsese and the film's editor, [[Thelma Schoonmaker]], made this sequence faster with more jump cuts to convey Henry's drug-addled point of view. In the first test screening there were 40 walkouts in the first ten minutes.<ref name=Kaplan /> One of the favorite scenes for test audiences was the \"Do I amuse you?\" scene.<ref name=Thompson />\n\n=== Soundtrack ===\n{{Main|Goodfellas (soundtrack)}}\nWhile there is no incidental score as such in the film, Scorsese chose songs for the soundtrack that he felt obliquely commented on the scene or the characters.<ref name=Gilbert /> In a given scene, he only used music contemporary to or older than the scene's setting. According to Scorsese, a lot of non-dialogue scenes were shot to playback. For example, he had \"[[Layla]]\" (1970) playing on the set while shooting the scene where the dead bodies are discovered in the car, dumpster, and meat truck. Sometimes, the lyrics of songs were put between lines of dialogue to comment on the action.<ref name=Thompson /> Some of the music Scorsese had written into the script, while other songs he discovered during the editing phase.<ref name=Kaplan />\n\n== Release ==\n===Theatrical===\n''Goodfellas'' premiered at the [[47th Venice International Film Festival]], where Scorsese received the [[Silver Lion]] award for [[Silver Lion#Silver Lion for Best Direction|best director]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Malcolm |first=Derek |title=The Venice Film Festival ends in uproar |newspaper=The Guardian |date=September 17, 1990}}</ref> It was given a wide release in North America on September 21, 1990.\n\n=== Home media ===\n''Goodfellas'' was released on [[DVD-Video|DVD]] in March 1997, in a single-disc, double-sided, single-layer format that requires the disc to be flipped during viewing; in 2004, [[Warner Home Video]] released a two-disc, dual-layer version, with [[remaster]]ed picture and sound, and bonus materials such as [[Audio commentary|commentary tracks]].<ref name=\"homevihist\" /> In early 2007 the film became available on single [[Blu-ray]] with all the features from the 2004 release; an expanded Blu-ray version was released in February 2010, bundled with a disc with features that include the 2008 documentary ''Public Enemies: The Golden Age of the Gangster Film.''<ref name=\"homevihist\">{{cite web |url=http://news.moviefone.com/2010/02/10/making-the-up-grade-goodfellas/ |title=Making The (Up) Grade: ''Goodfellas'' |date=February 10, 2010 |first=Todd |last=Gilchrist |publisher=[[Moviefone]] |accessdate=August 27, 2014 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140827133312/http://news.moviefone.com/2010/02/10/making-the-up-grade-goodfellas/ | archive-date= August 27, 2014 | url-status= dead}}</ref> The film was released on 4K [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]] on December 6, 2016.<ref>{{Citation |title=GoodFellas 4K Blu-ray |url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/GoodFellas-4K-Blu-ray/161258/ |accessdate=January 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201020210/http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/GoodFellas-4K-Blu-ray/161258/|archive-date=February 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Box office ===\n''Goodfellas'' opened in 1,070 theaters, with an opening weekend gross of [[United States dollar|US$]]6.3 million. It went on to make $46.8 million domestically.<ref name=\"Box Office Mojo\">{{cite web |title=Goodfellas |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=goodfellas.htm |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=December 7, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218124834/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=goodfellas.htm|archive-date=December 18, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a 96% approval score based on 96 reviews, with an average rating of 8.99/10. The website's consensus reads, \"Hard-hitting and stylish, ''GoodFellas'' is a gangster classic\u2014and arguably the high point of Martin Scorsese's career.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1032176_goodfellas |title=Goodfellas (1990) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=November 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817123029/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1032176_goodfellas|archive-date=August 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned the film a score of 90 out of 100 based on 20 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/goodfellas |title=Goodfellas (1990) |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=September 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706220854/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/goodfellas|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2212\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |website=[[CinemaScore]] |accessdate=September 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104063502/https://www.cinemascore.com/|archive-date=January 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn his review for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', [[Roger Ebert]] wrote, \"No finer film has ever been made about organized crime \u2013 not even ''[[The Godfather]]''.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19900902/REVIEWS/9020301 |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |title=GoodFellas |date=September 2, 1990 |accessdate=October 18, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111122457/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F19900902%2FREVIEWS%2F9020301|archive-date=January 11, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In his review for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', [[Gene Siskel]] wrote, \"All of the performances are first-rate; Pesci stands out, though, with his seemingly unscripted manner. ''GoodFellas'' is easily one of the year's best films.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-09-21/entertainment/9003190299_1_goodfellas-henry-hill-mob |title=Scorsese's 'Goodfellas' One Of The Year's Best |last=Siskel |first=Gene |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=September 21, 1990 |accessdate=October 18, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028162829/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-09-21/entertainment/9003190299_1_goodfellas-henry-hill-mob|archive-date=October 28, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Both named it as the best film of 1990. In his review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Vincent Canby]] wrote, \"More than any earlier Scorsese film, ''Goodfellas'' is memorable for the ensemble nature of the performances... The movie has been beautifully cast from the leading roles to the bits. There is flash also in some of Mr. Scorsese's directorial choices, including freeze frames, [[fast cutting]] and the occasional long tracking shot. None of it is superfluous.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Canby |first=Vincent |title=A Cold-Eyed Look at the Mob's Inner Workings |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 19, 1990}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' gave the film four out of four stars and called it, \"great cinema\u2014and also a whopping good time.\"<ref name=Clark /> [[David Ansen]], in his review for ''[[Newsweek]]'' magazine, wrote \"Every crisp minute of this long, teeming movie vibrates with outlaw energy.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Ansen |first=David |title=A Hollywood Crime Wave |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=September 17, 1990}}</ref> [[Rex Reed]] said, \"Big, rich, powerful and explosive. One of Scorsese's best films! ''Goodfellas'' is great entertainment.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Reed |first=Rex |date=September 24, 1990 |title=Goodfellas |magazine=New York Magazine |location= |publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> In his review for ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', [[Richard Corliss]] wrote, \"So it is Scorsese's triumph that ''GoodFellas'' offers the fastest, sharpest 2\u00bd-hr. ride in recent film history.\"<ref name=\"Corliss\">{{cite news |last=Corliss |first=Richard |title=Married to the Mob |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=September 24, 1990 |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,971220,00.html |accessdate=January 29, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220094359/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,971220,00.html|archive-date=February 20, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Lists ===\nThe film was ranked the best of 1990 by Roger Ebert,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |url=http://www.innermind.com/misc/s_e_top.htm |title=Siskel and Ebert Top Ten Lists (1969\u20131998) |publisher=Innermind.com |date=May 3, 2012 |accessdate=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6GWJx7Em0?url=http://www.innermind.com/misc/s_e_top.htm |archive-date=May 10, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> Gene Siskel,<ref name=autogenerated1 /> and Peter Travers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alumnus.caltech.edu/~ejohnson/critics/travers.html |title=Peter Travers' Top Ten Lists 1989\u20132005 |publisher=caltech.edu |date= |accessdate=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206120135/http://alumnus.caltech.edu/~ejohnson/critics/travers.html |archive-date=February 6, 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the [[Motion Picture Editors Guild]] listed ''Goodfellas'' as the fifteenth best-edited film of all time based on a survey of its membership.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The 75 Best Edited Films |journal=Editors Guild Magazine |date=May 2012 |volume=1 |issue=3 |url=https://www.editorsguild.com/magazine.cfm?ArticleID=1102 |access-date=April 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317101140/https://www.editorsguild.com/magazine.cfm?ArticleID=1102 |archive-date=March 17, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Goodfellas'' is 39th on [[James Berardinelli]]'s 2014-made list of the top 100 films of all time.<ref>{{cite web |last=Berardinelli |first=James |url=http://www.reelviews.net/specials/james-berardinelli-s-all-time-top-100 |title=Berardinelli's All Time Top 100 |publisher=Reelviews.net |date=2014 |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410133026/http://www.reelviews.net/specials/james-berardinelli-s-all-time-top-100 |archive-date=April 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#bcbcbc;\"| Award\n! style=\"background:#bcbcbc;\"| Category\n! style=\"background:#bcbcbc;\"| Nominee\n! style=\"background:#bcbcbc;\"| Result\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[63rd Academy Awards|Academy Award]]\n|[[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]]<ref name=63rdAcAwards />\n|[[Martin Scorsese]] and [[Irwin Winkler]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]]<ref name=63rdAcAwards />\n|Martin Scorsese\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]]<ref name=63rdAcAwards />\n|[[Thelma Schoonmaker]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]<ref name=63rdAcAwards />\n|Martin Scorsese and [[Nicholas Pileggi]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]<ref name=63rdAcAwards>{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/63rd.html/ |title=The 63rd Academy Awards (1991) |publisher=Oscars.org |date= |accessdate=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322193640/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/63rd.html |archive-date=March 22, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|[[Joe Pesci]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]<ref name=63rdAcAwards />\n|[[Lorraine Bracco]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[48th Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]]\n|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Drama|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Drama]]<ref name=\"GoldenGlobes-Goodfellas\">{{cite web |title=HFPA \u2013 Awards Search |url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/film/24169 |accessdate=August 27, 2014 |archiveurl=