a |title='Cheers' brings happy times to NBC |work=USA TODAY |date=26 May 1993}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Logan and Briscoe begin their investigation into the death of a hearing-impaired young woman by questioning her two most recent boyfriends.\n* Last appearances of [[Dann Florek]] as Capt. [[Don Cragen]] and [[Richard Brooks (actor)|Richard Brooks]] as ADA [[Paul Robinette]] as series regulars.\n |LineColor=000000\n}}\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n* [[Eric Bogosian]], who guest starred as a defense attorney in the episodes \"Conspiracy\" and \"Night and Fog\", would later have a starring role in the ''Law & Order'' spin-off, ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent|Criminal Intent]]''.\n\n==External links==\n* {{tv.com show|law-order|Law & Order}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060612233143/http://www.nbc.com/Law_%26_Order/episode_guide/ Episode guide from NBC.com]\n\n{{Law & Order}}\n\n{{sequence|\nprev=[[Law & Order (season 2)|Season Two]]<br />(1991\u20131992)|\nlist=[[List of Law & Order seasons#Series overview|List of Law & Order seasons]]<br />(1990\u20132010)|\nnext=[[Law & Order (season 4)|Season Four]]<br />(1993\u20131994)|}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Law And Order episodes (season 3), List of}}\n[[Category:Lists of Law & Order episodes by season|03]]\n[[Category:1992 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:1993 American television seasons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television season\n| season_number        = 3\n| bgcolour             = #000000\n| image                = LawAndOrder S3.jpg\n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = Season 3 U.S. DVD cover\n| starring             = \n| country              = [[Television in the United States|United States]]\n| num_episodes         = 22\n| network              = [[National Broadcasting Company|NBC]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|1992|9|23}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|1993|5|19}}\n| prev_season          = [[Law & Order (season 2)|Season 2]]\n| next_season          = [[Law & Order (season 4)|Season 4]]\n| episode_list         = List of Law & Order episodes\n}}\n\nThe third season of ''[[Law & Order]]'' aired on [[NBC]] between September 23, 1992, and May 19, 1993. This season marked the introduction of [[Jerry Orbach]] as [[Lennie Briscoe]], who replaced [[Paul Sorvino]] after \"Prince of Darkness.\" (A year prior, Orbach had guest starred as a defense attorney in at least one episode season two episode two\u2019s \u201cWages of Love\u201d). At the end of the season, both [[Dann Florek]] and [[Richard Brooks (actor)|Richard Brooks]] departed the main cast.\n\n==Cast==\nSeason 3 began with an unchanged cast.  However, during the third and sixth episode, [[Carolyn McCormick]] was credited in the opening theme and starting with the ninth episode, she is credited for the rest of the season. This made her the first woman to be part of the cast in the series. A third of the way through, [[Lennie Briscoe]] (played by [[Jerry Orbach]]) replaced [[Phil Cerreta]] ([[Paul Sorvino]]) in the role of senior detective. This was the first mid-season replacement of a major character in ''Law & Order'''s history; the next would not occur until [[Law & Order (season 15)|season 15]]. This was also the final season to feature [[Dann Florek]] as Capt. [[Don Cragen]], and [[Richard Brooks (actor)|Richard Brooks]] as [[Paul Robinette]].  Both men would later return in guest roles, with Florek eventually joining the cast of ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''.\n\n* [[Paul Sorvino]] as [[Phil Cerreta|Sgt. Phil Cerreta]]\n* [[Jerry Orbach]] as [[Lennie Briscoe|Det. Lennie Briscoe]]\n* [[Chris Noth]] as [[Mike Logan (Law & Order)|Det. Mike Logan]]\n* [[Dann Florek]] as [[Don Cragen|Capt. Don Cragen]]\n* [[Michael Moriarty]] as [[Benjamin Stone (character)|E.A.D.A. Ben Stone]]\n* [[Richard Brooks (actor)|Richard Brooks]] as [[Paul Robinette|A.D.A. Paul Robinette]]\n* [[Steven Hill]] as [[Adam Schiff (Law & Order)|D.A. Adam Schiff]]\n* [[Carolyn McCormick]] as [[Elizabeth Olivet|Dr. Elizabeth Olivet]]\n\n==Episodes==\n<onlyinclude>\n{{#invoke:Episode table|main\n|background  = #000000\n|overall     = \n|season      = \n|title       = \n|director    =\n|writer      = \n|airdate     = \n|prodcode    = \n|viewers     = \n|country     = US\n|episodes    = \n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Law & Order (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=45\n |EpisodeNumber2=1\n |Title=Skin Deep\n |DirectedBy=[[Daniel Sackheim]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Robert Stuart Nathan|Robert Nathan]] & [[Gordon Rayfield]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1992|9|23}}\n |ProdCode=68009\n |Aux4=14.90{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n |ShortSummary=After photographer Julian Decker is found murdered in his studio, Logan and Cerreta discover that Decker's real business was prostitution and acting as a pimp for models who aren't getting the work they needed. Their investigation leads to Angela Brandt, one of Decker's models who found more money working for Decker in other ways, but they also discover that Decker was romantically involved with Angela's teenage daughter. Stone realizes that something strange is going on when the case gets weaker against Angela, but all of a sudden she wants to cut a deal.\n* [[Gina Torres]] guest-stars as Laura Elkin, who finds Decker's body.\n |LineColor=000000\n}}{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Law & Order (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=46\n |EpisodeNumber2=2\n |Title=Conspiracy\n |DirectedBy=[[Edwin Sherin|Ed Sherin]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Michael S. Chernuchin]] & [[Ren\u00e9 Balcer]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1992|9|30}}\n |ProdCode=68006\n |Aux4=12.80{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n |ShortSummary=After Marcus Tate, the respected leader of a controversial African-American rights movement, is assassinated at a rally, Logan and Cerreta attempt to get information on the crime but are stonewalled by many of Tate's followers, who aren't interested in talking to white police officers. Photographs lead them to Mitchell Kolbin, a white man who had followed Tate religiously but who seemed to lose some of his wonderment when Tate began an affair with his wife.\n |LineColor=000000\n}}{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Law & Order (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=47\n |EpisodeNumber2=3\n |Title=Forgiveness\n |DirectedBy=[[Bill D'Elia]]\n |WrittenBy={{StoryTeleplay\n | s = Robert Nathan;\n | ex1 = Ed Zuckerman\n | slabel = {{abbr|S|Story by}}\n | ex1label = {{abbr|S/T|Story and teleplay by}}\n }}\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1992|10|7}}\n |ProdCode=68005\n |Aux4=17.20{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n |ShortSummary=After Beth Milgram is found beaten to death in an alleyway after her going away party, Logan and Cerreta initially turn their suspicion to the girl's father after her fianc\u00e9, Tommy Beltran, claims that he had hit her after Beth told him they were engaged, but it isn't long before their primary suspect becomes Beltran himself. Stone has the unpleasant task of facing the renowned Cyrus Weaver, who is determined to prove that Tommy Beltran is not guilty of murdering Beth Milgram because he was a poor young man from a Mexican family who could not restrain his rage when his upper-class girlfriend broke up with him. (Plot derived from [[Bonnie Garland murder case]].)\n |LineColor=000000\n}}{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Law & Order (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=48\n |EpisodeNumber2=4\n |Title=The Corporate Veil\n |DirectedBy=[[Don Scardino]]\n |WrittenBy=Michael S. Chernuchin & Joe Morgenstern\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1992|10|14}}\n |ProdCode=68007\n |Aux4=14.80{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n |ShortSummary= while Cerreta and Logan are investigating death of a teenage boy who had a fatal heart attack is traced to a wealthy business company for fraud and greed on the part of the manufacturer of his pacemaker and their supplier.\n |LineColor=000000\n}}{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Law & Order (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=49\n |EpisodeNumber2=5\n |Title=Wedded Bliss\n |DirectedBy=[[Vern Gillum]]\n |WrittenBy=Robert Nathan & Edward Pomerantz\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1992|10|21}}\n |ProdCode=68004\n |Aux4=14.80<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gable |first1=Donna |title=Baseball cleans up for CBS |work=USA TODAY |date=28 October 1992}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=The discovery of a young woman's body in the river leads to an investigation of illegal sweatshops and the enslavement of young immigrants.\n |LineColor=000000\n}}{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Law & Order (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=50\n |EpisodeNumber2=6\n |Title=Helpless\n |DirectedBy=[[James Frawley]]\n |WrittenBy=Michael S. Chernuchin & Christine Roum\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1992|11|4}}\n |ProdCode=68011\n |Aux4=17.50<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gable |first1=Donna |title=Election news, football kick up ABS's ratings |work=USA TODAY |date=11 November 1992}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Dr. Olivet accuses her gynecologist of rape, but Stone finds his case in trouble when he discovers that Olivet tape-recorded the crime.\n |LineColor=000000\n}}{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Law & Order (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=51\n |EpisodeNumber2=7\n |Title=Self-Defense\n |DirectedBy=Ed Sherin\n |WrittenBy=Ren\u00e9 Balcer & Hall Powell\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1992|11|11}}\n |ProdCode=68008\n |Aux4=14.90<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gable |first1=Donna |title='Jacksons,' solid gold for ABC |work=USA TODAY |date=18 November 1992}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=The detectives and prosecutors find themselves on opposite sides of the fence when a storeowner name George Costas shot and kills two robbers and then claims self-defense as a justification.\n |LineColor=000000\n}}{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Law & Order (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=52\n |EpisodeNumber2=8\n |Title=Prince of Darkness\n |DirectedBy=Gilbert Shilton\n |WrittenBy=Robert Nathan & William N. Fordes\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1992|11|18}}\n |ProdCode=68003\n |Aux4=14.60<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gable |first1=Donna |title=Jacksons help as-easy-as-ABC win |work=USA TODAY |date=25 November 1992}}</re